The article is a statement by the President on the observance of Juneteenth. It highlights the significance of Juneteenth, which marks the day when the people of Galveston, Texas, were informed by the Union Army that slaves were now free, more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed by President Lincoln. The statement emphasizes that Juneteenth is a time to celebrate the rich heritage and accomplishments of African Americans in the United States, as well as reflect on the shared values and ideals that all Americans possess. It also acknowledges the struggles for equal rights and social justice that have made the nation stronger, and the contributions of African Americans to American culture throughout history. The article concludes by stating that Juneteenth, although rooted in the history of a specific group of people, can be celebrated by all Americans.